@PatrickMassot I have closed #12179 and ported the modifications _ibid_ in this PR, where they are used to prove the completeness of Laurent series.

@AntoineChambert-Loir I have addressed all your points concerning the file `LaurentSeries.lean` (with a comment that generalizing to arbitrary Hahn series seems hard at the moment). I will tackle the other comments about the discrete topology tomorrow. Thank you very much for your thorough review!

I have added a remark concerning the potential extension to Hahn Series, while I think that the comment about the result holding already for the discrete topology is false as discussed with @AntoineChambert-Loir on Zulip.
It looks good to me. Thanks!

Thanks :tada:

Oh sure, when I sent it to bors everything was green (or at least I believe): I wonder if it is possible that some conflict emerged while bors was merging another batch of PR's, or if I was just too sloppy, Johan's warning notwhistanding.
bors r+

Pull request successfully merged into master.

Build succeeded:
  * [Build](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/actions/runs/11131089137/job/30931875212)
  * [Lint style](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/actions/runs/11131089137/job/30931875905)

My comments are minor, it may not be necessary that they are implemented (if they work as planned), but what holds mathematically should be recorded in the file so as to prepare for further work of other people.
The name suggests that LHS and RHS should be swapped.
Done, but I added an "of".

```suggestion
theorem eq_singleton_left_of_prod_subset_idRel {X : Type _} {S T : Set X} (hS : S.Nonempty)
    (hT : T.Nonempty) (h_diag : S ×ˢ T ⊆ idRel) : ∃ x, S = {x} := by
```

```suggestion
theorem eq_singleton_right_prod_subset_idRel {X : Type _} {S T : Set X} (hS : S.Nonempty)
```

```suggestion
theorem eq_singleton_prod_subset_idRel {X : Type _} {S T : Set X} (hS : S.Nonempty)
```
Can you qualify the lemmas in the docstring? For example, `LaurentSeries.uniformContinuous_coeff`…
Done, good catch.
I have the (mathematical) impression that the theorem does not really need the hypothesis that the coefficient has the discrete uniformity.
Indeed! Thanks, I could simply remove the hypothesis (with a minor modification of a line). Awesome.
`LaurentSeries K`
Here, I'm certain that the fact that one uses Laurent series is not needed, the same proof would probably show that Hahn series are complete.

Well, my problem here is that I make strong use of an explicit description of the uniformity on `LaurentSeries K` coming from its `Valued` group structure, where entourages are defined in terms of the `X`-adic valuation. Nothing of this is currently available for Hahn series. I can of course make a remark (or you can add it to this PR, please do feel free!) but I fear that generalizing the result now would result in a gigantic refactor.
Then a remark will be OK. Ultimately people will prove that the natural topology on Hahn series is complete, and that for Z, it gives the topology given by the valuation.
maybe: “has a lower bound” (to explain the discrepancy with the next theorem)
`LaurentSeries K`.
`Cauchy`. (And maybe adjust the rest)
Thanks, fixed.
I would prefer to read `ℱ.sets_of_superset` rather than `ℱ.3`
I have the impression that the use of `H` is not that necessary (so that the `by_cases H` earlier maybe too complicated than needed).
Nice remark, I have significantly improved the proof, it is much nicer now. Thanks!
Here, it should suffice that the *topology* is discrete (whatever the uniform structure is).
(And even a bit less : it suffices that all points be open)
This should hold for the discrete topology.
(NB. Points open + T2 means that points are open and closed, so the topology is discrete.)

```suggestion
coefficient is uniformly continuous, ensuring that it sends a Cauchy filter `ℱ` in `LaurentSeries K`
```

I suggest calling this `limit` (in the appropriate namespaces)
```suggestion
def Cauchy.limit {ℱ : Filter (LaurentSeries K)} (hℱ : Cauchy ℱ) : LaurentSeries K :=
```
If you agree, please also update the mention of this name in a comment below.
Yes, given we're in the LaurentSeries namespace this makes sense. Updating.
I think this one deserves to be mentioned in the module docstring. Or maybe the instance below, if you give it a name.
Done, I have called `instLaurentSeriesComplete` the instance below, and mentioned it in the namespace.
Do you really need to give the instance a name? Can't it be generated automatically?
Yes, it could (and it was), but one of @jcommelin 's requests was that I mention it explicitly in the docstring, and for this it needs to be named.

OK. My impression was that instances get named automatically, and hence you could use/document the name even if you let Lean compute it for you. (I admit this makes the docstring sensitive to a future change in the naming process.)

Yes, they are but their name don't appear. You can use `#synth` to see what has been created automatically, but since the name does not appear in print any textual search would fail (for now it is the last bit of the file, but if later on more things are added, it might be useful to be able to search for its name and to jump to the right line).
